where \(im\) denotes the raw image, \(()\) a encoder, and \(()\) a quantizer. The quantizer typically includes a learnable codebook \(Z^{V C}\) containing \(V\) vectors. The quantization process \(q=(f)\) will map each feature vector \(f^{(i,j)}\) to the code index \(q^{(i,j)}\) of its nearest code in the Euclidean sense:

\[q^{(i,j)}=(*{arg\,min}_{v[V]}\|(Z,v)-f^{ (i,j)}\|_{2})[V], \]

where \((Z,v)\) means taking the \(v\)-th vector in codebook \(Z\). To train the quantized autoencoder, \(Z\) is looked up by every \(q^{(i,j)}\) to get \(\), the approximation of original \(f\). Then a new image \(\) is reconstructed using the decoder \(()\) given \(\), and a compound loss \(\) is minimized:

